1
00:00:01,802 --> 00:00:19,574
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:20,146 --> 00:00:34,313
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Bharato Sama Sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,332 --> 00:00:41,225
So I thought, since it's been a while since we've done a proper Buddha Day here actually,

4
00:00:41,206 --> 00:00:57,941
I thought just to go over his journey, I was going to quote this Mahasachakasutta, the long sutta, the long discourse around this fellow called Sachaka, whom the Buddha also refers to as Ajisena, which is his family name.

5
00:00:59,902 --> 00:01:04,987
So this is the Buddha expressing what he went through, his mortifications.

6
00:01:06,448 --> 00:01:10,673
Then it occurred to me, why don't I practice the breathless absorption?

7
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:23,637
So I cut off my breathing through my mouth and nose and ears, and then there was an intense burning in my body like two strong men grabbing a weaker man by the arms to burn and scorch him on a pit of glowing coals.

8
00:01:24,638 --> 00:01:35,493
My energy was roused and unflagging, and my mindfulness was established and lucid, but my body was disturbed, not tranquil, because I had pushed too hard with this painful striving.

9
00:01:36,155 --> 00:01:39,900
But even such painful feelings did not overcome my awareness."

10
00:01:40,893 --> 00:01:41,534
Have you tried that?

11
00:01:43,757 --> 00:01:50,105
I can't quite visualize it somehow.

12
00:01:50,126 --> 00:01:50,447
Anyway.

13
00:01:51,388 --> 00:01:55,174
Then some deities saw me and said, the ascetic Gautama is dead.

14
00:01:55,274 --> 00:01:57,798
And others said, he's not dead, he's dying.

15
00:01:58,378 --> 00:02:00,561
And others said, he's not dead or dying.

16
00:02:00,921 --> 00:02:03,846
He's the ascetic Gautama as a perfected one.

17
00:02:03,865 --> 00:02:05,709
For that is how the perfected ones live.

18
00:02:06,430 --> 00:02:08,293
Well, he isn't the perfected one yet.

19
00:02:09,274 --> 00:02:09,735
So there's a

20
00:02:10,254 --> 00:02:13,825
They've misunderstood his efforts.

21
00:02:14,086 --> 00:02:14,769
So that failed.

22
00:02:15,189 --> 00:02:19,522
Then it occurred to me, why don't I practice completely cutting off food?

23
00:02:20,295 --> 00:02:24,782
But the deities came to me and said, good sir, don't practice totally cutting off food.

24
00:02:24,962 --> 00:02:30,229
If you do, we'll infuse divine nectar into your pores and you'll live on that.

25
00:02:30,931 --> 00:02:40,503
Then I thought, if I claim to be completely fasting while these deities are infusing divine nectar in my pores, that would be a lie on my part.

26
00:02:40,524 --> 00:02:43,168
So I dismissed these deities and said there's no need.

27
00:02:45,050 --> 00:02:46,151
Then it occurred to me,

28
00:02:46,621 --> 00:02:53,888
Why don't I take a little bit of food each time, a cup of broth made of mung beans, horse gram, chickpeas or green gram?

29
00:02:54,367 --> 00:02:58,292
So that's what I did until my body became extremely emaciated.

30
00:02:58,953 --> 00:03:04,918
Due to eating so little, my limbs became like the joints of an eight-year-old or the corpse.

31
00:03:05,558 --> 00:03:07,760
My bottom became like a camel's hoof.

32
00:03:08,701 --> 00:03:16,188
My vertebrae stuck out like beads on a string and my ribs were as gaunt as the broken down rafters on an old barn.

33
00:03:16,826 --> 00:03:24,675
Due to eating so little, the gleam in my eyes sank deep in their sockets like the gleam of water sunk deep down in a well.

34
00:03:25,575 --> 00:03:32,323
Due to eating so little, my scalp shriveled and withered like a green bitter gourd in the wind and sun.

35
00:03:33,123 --> 00:03:41,872
Due to eating so little, the skin of my belly stuck to the backbone, so that when I tried to rub the skin of my belly, I grabbed my backbone.

36
00:03:42,359 --> 00:03:46,485
And when I tried to rub my backbone, I rubbed the skin of my belly.

37
00:03:47,407 --> 00:03:53,396
Due to eating so little, when I tried to urinate or defecate, I fell face down right there.

38
00:03:54,459 --> 00:04:03,674
Due to eating so little, when I tried to relieve my body by rubbing my limbs with my hands, the hair rotted at its roots and fell out.

39
00:04:04,395 --> 00:04:07,539
Then some people said, the ascetic Gautama is black.

40
00:04:07,942 --> 00:04:10,004
Some said, he's not black, he's brown.

41
00:04:10,365 --> 00:04:12,807
And some said, no, he's neither black nor brown.

42
00:04:13,128 --> 00:04:16,151
The ascetic Gautama has tawny skin.

43
00:04:16,172 --> 00:04:22,000
That's how far the pure and bright complexion of my skin had been ruined by taking so little food.

44
00:04:23,541 --> 00:04:32,413
Then I thought, whatever ascetics and Brahmins have experienced painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings due to overexertion,

45
00:04:33,119 --> 00:04:37,305
Whether in the past, future or present, this is as far as it goes.

46
00:04:37,826 --> 00:04:39,487
No one has done more than this.

47
00:04:40,149 --> 00:04:49,322
But I have not achieved any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones by this severe, grueling work.

48
00:04:49,781 --> 00:04:52,605
Could there be another path to awakening?

49
00:04:53,487 --> 00:04:57,132
So he's telling us that he took these, you know, ascetic practices to their limit.

50
00:04:58,413 --> 00:05:00,476
Now, that one about the about

51
00:05:00,675 --> 00:05:13,497
not eating, that seems to have been because he had some sort of, I don't know whether it was a relationship, but he sort of knew about the Jains.

52
00:05:13,737 --> 00:05:15,961
And the Jain teacher was an elder contemporary.

53
00:05:16,983 --> 00:05:24,776
And in that teaching, what your body, your physical body is an expression of your personal karma.

54
00:05:25,567 --> 00:05:31,759
So by letting go of the body completely, your soul would then rise naturally into heaven.

55
00:05:31,778 --> 00:05:35,446
And Jains to this day, you know, when they're very old, they'll just stop eating.

56
00:05:35,706 --> 00:05:37,810
It's the way they choose to die.

57
00:05:39,312 --> 00:05:40,656
Often, not always.

58
00:05:41,850 --> 00:05:54,394
So then, by the way, those descriptions of him starving, it does remind you of the pictures we've seen of people suffering from famines.

59
00:05:54,875 --> 00:05:56,317
So you have to have that in mind.

60
00:05:59,382 --> 00:06:03,370
Stemming from that memory came the realisation that

61
00:06:03,517 --> 00:06:04,399
Oh, just a minute.

62
00:06:04,959 --> 00:06:05,360
That's right.

63
00:06:05,439 --> 00:06:06,420
Then it occurred to me.

64
00:06:07,182 --> 00:06:12,968
I recall sitting in a cool shade of the rose apple tree while my father, the saccharine, was off working.

65
00:06:13,709 --> 00:06:27,182
Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, I entered and remained in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing awareness and keeping it connected.

66
00:06:27,762 --> 00:06:29,365
Could that be the path to awakening?

67
00:06:30,005 --> 00:06:32,427
Now, he had...

68
00:06:32,627 --> 00:06:41,899
Practise these jhanas, remember, right at the beginning, according to the usual way that we see the way his life spanned out.

69
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:49,470
He went, first of all, to two teachers who taught him how to practise these absorption states, which are very delightful.

70
00:06:49,550 --> 00:06:50,831
You do it inside yourself, yeah?

71
00:06:51,211 --> 00:06:53,596
You don't need anything outside, yeah?

72
00:06:53,615 --> 00:07:02,247
So, if you practise loving-kindness and you get beautiful feelings, and they're such beautiful feelings, that's all you want to do all day, sit on a tree and practise loving-kindness, yeah?

73
00:07:03,290 --> 00:07:31,355
so you don't need anything at all apart from a bit of food so he had dismissed that so the distinction here i think when he says while placing awareness and keeping it connected so there's a dis there's a suggestion there that he's caught on to the idea that although he's practicing these jhanas they become themselves the object of investigation right

74
00:07:31,723 --> 00:07:34,310
Then it occurred to me, why am I afraid of that pleasure?

75
00:07:34,331 --> 00:07:38,101
For it's nothing to do with sensual pleasures or unskillful qualities.

76
00:07:38,564 --> 00:07:45,041
Then I thought, I'm not afraid of that pleasure, for it has nothing to do with sensual pleasure or unskillful qualities.

77
00:07:45,629 --> 00:07:50,276
Then I thought, I can't achieve that pleasure with the body so excessively emaciated.

78
00:07:50,858 --> 00:07:54,023
Why don't I eat some solid food, some rice and porridge?

79
00:07:54,403 --> 00:07:55,725
So I ate some solid food.

80
00:07:56,226 --> 00:08:04,060
Now at that time, the five mendicants who were attending on me, they weren't actually, I don't know why it's translated to that, who were his companions.

81
00:08:04,040 --> 00:08:27,245
thinking the ascetic gotama will tell us of any truth that he realizes but when he ate some solid food they felt disappointed in me saying the ascetic gotama has become indulgent he has strayed from the struggle and returned to indulgence after eating solid food and gathering my strength quite secluded from sensual pleasures secluded from unskillful qualities

82
00:08:27,529 --> 00:08:29,612
So the greed wasn't there, remember?

83
00:08:30,192 --> 00:08:37,698
I entered and remained in the first absorption, which has rapture and bliss, born of seclusion, while placing the awareness and keeping it connected.

84
00:08:38,419 --> 00:08:42,023
But even such pleasant feeling did not occupy my mind.

85
00:08:42,423 --> 00:08:56,135
Ah, so this tells you that here he's understood that the jhanas themselves become a way of investigation, whereas before when he'd started the path, he would absorb into them and just enjoy them.

86
00:08:56,470 --> 00:09:01,455
So in other words, it's put here, did not occupy my mind.

87
00:09:01,615 --> 00:09:07,140
A better translation would be, and even such feeling did not occupy my awareness.

88
00:09:07,542 --> 00:09:18,613
So if you read that statement on the window ledge out there from the Ararat Meji Kiao, you'll see that's exactly what she says.

89
00:09:19,793 --> 00:09:25,059
Everything comes in front of the awareness and never enters into what she calls her heart.

90
00:09:26,591 --> 00:09:46,663
So when my mind was immersed in Samadhi like this, purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruption, pliable, workable, steady and unperturbable, I extended it towards recollection of past lives and I recollected my many kinds of past lives with features and details.

91
00:09:47,024 --> 00:09:51,029
This was the first knowledge that I achieved in the first watch of the night.

92
00:09:51,432 --> 00:09:54,015
Ignorance was destroyed and knowledge arose.

93
00:09:54,376 --> 00:10:00,687
Darkness was destroyed and light arose, as happens for a meditator who is diligent, keen and resolute.

94
00:10:01,388 --> 00:10:04,894
But even such pleasant feelings did not occupy my awareness.

95
00:10:05,696 --> 00:10:13,288
So this is where he understands that all his past lives were driven by his actions, his karma.

96
00:10:13,706 --> 00:10:16,812
We'll come to something else in a minute.

97
00:10:17,272 --> 00:10:32,274
So now in the next watch, when my mind was immersed in Samadhi like this, purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady and imperturbable, I extended it towards the knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.

98
00:10:33,096 --> 00:10:41,368
And with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, I saw sentient beings passing away and being reborn, inferior or superior,

99
00:10:41,668 --> 00:10:49,240
beautiful or ugly, in a good place or a bad place, and I understood how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.

100
00:10:50,020 --> 00:10:57,993
So here he's understood the law of karma is not just his personal law, but it's a universal law.

101
00:10:58,013 --> 00:11:07,086
And it's interesting, later on we'll just mention these four levels of attainment, the stream entrance, once returner, non-returner,

102
00:11:07,673 --> 00:11:22,219
And in the commentaries, it says anybody who understands the law of karma is a chula sotapanna, so is a lesser sotapanna, a lesser stream entrant, by which is meant anybody who understands the law of karma is already on the path.

103
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:26,947
It's inevitable that they will become liberated in the goodness of time.

104
00:11:28,835 --> 00:11:40,589
Then when my mind was immersed in samadhi like this, purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady and imperturbable, I extended it towards the knowledge of the ending of defilements.

105
00:11:41,330 --> 00:11:43,471
I truly understood this is suffering.

106
00:11:43,552 --> 00:11:44,933
This is the origin of suffering.

107
00:11:45,533 --> 00:11:47,176
This is the cessation of suffering.

108
00:11:47,196 --> 00:11:50,320
This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.

109
00:11:50,705 --> 00:11:53,488
I truly understood these are defilements.

110
00:11:53,668 --> 00:11:55,590
This is the origin of defilements.

111
00:11:55,691 --> 00:11:57,732
This is the cessation of defilements.

112
00:11:58,232 --> 00:12:02,077
And this is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements.

113
00:12:02,739 --> 00:12:10,807
Knowing and seeing this, my mind was freed from defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn and ignorance.

114
00:12:10,827 --> 00:12:13,230
And when it was freed, I knew it was freed.

115
00:12:13,551 --> 00:12:16,874
OK, so when he attained liberation, he knew it.

116
00:12:17,095 --> 00:12:20,138
He knew he was completely free of these defilements.

117
00:12:20,658 --> 00:12:29,750
Now this world of defilements, usually it's understood to be those things that come because of our immoral, unwholesome actions.

118
00:12:30,370 --> 00:12:31,312
But it's more than that.

119
00:12:31,852 --> 00:12:36,860
It's also the defilements that come from this fundamental misunderstanding about self.

120
00:12:37,701 --> 00:12:43,188
So one of the things that arises because of that misunderstanding is fear.

121
00:12:43,355 --> 00:12:43,654
Right?

122
00:12:43,674 --> 00:12:46,559
So, fear of death, fear of illness, fear of others.

123
00:12:47,080 --> 00:12:49,624
So, that fear is also a defilement.

124
00:12:50,365 --> 00:12:53,971
And later, they made a list of these ten defilements.

125
00:12:54,010 --> 00:13:00,399
But actually, the way he uses defilements in the scriptures is just anything which arises out of this ignorance.

126
00:13:01,321 --> 00:13:07,870
And the basic ignorance, the basic delusion is to believe we are human beings in a complete total way.

127
00:13:08,451 --> 00:13:08,552
Okay?

128
00:13:10,607 --> 00:13:11,808
So I understood.

129
00:13:11,828 --> 00:13:12,850
I understood.

130
00:13:12,890 --> 00:13:13,971
Rebirth is ended.

131
00:13:14,613 --> 00:13:16,695
The spiritual journey has been complete.

132
00:13:17,836 --> 00:13:19,938
What had to be done has been done.

133
00:13:20,539 --> 00:13:23,023
There is no return to any state of becoming.

134
00:13:23,643 --> 00:13:24,884
That's a lovely little phrase there.

135
00:13:24,924 --> 00:13:27,567
What had to be done has been done.

136
00:13:28,428 --> 00:13:35,576
You can feel the release, the relief of having finally arrived at the place of liberation.

137
00:13:36,557 --> 00:13:40,462
This was the third knowledge that I achieved in the last watch of the night.

138
00:13:40,763 --> 00:13:54,062
Ignorance was destroyed, knowledge arose, darkness was destroyed and light arose, as happens for a meditator who is diligent, keen and resolute, but even such pleasant feeling did not occupy my awareness.

139
00:13:55,585 --> 00:14:02,215
So that's the ending of that sort of discourse where he describes how he finally attained liberation.

140
00:14:02,919 --> 00:14:19,034
So we've talked about these defilements, and one of the discourses is on the abayasu, to where he's in the jungle training, and this great fear comes upon him, wild animals, etc., etc., and he has to overcome that.

141
00:14:19,495 --> 00:14:24,559
So that's not caused by some unwholesome action.

142
00:14:24,600 --> 00:14:31,846
That's just part of the structure that comes when you have a sense of self, of this body being a sense of self.

143
00:14:32,164 --> 00:14:35,049
So when the body's in danger, then you get that fear.

144
00:14:35,370 --> 00:14:38,355
And that would be included in defilements.

145
00:14:39,817 --> 00:14:50,657
And also these days when we talk about trauma from childhood and things like that, that's also part of the defilements, which is not caused by personal wrongdoing or anything.

146
00:14:50,716 --> 00:14:55,404
It's just something that arises because of our fundamental delusion.

147
00:14:57,038 --> 00:15:05,427
So these four attainments, the stream entrant, he says it's like a flash of lightning.

148
00:15:05,647 --> 00:15:12,294
So a person who has that stream entrant sees everything, but on the other hand, it's not deep, it's just a flash.

149
00:15:13,816 --> 00:15:19,822
And often when a person does have that sort of experience, they can't really...

150
00:15:20,495 --> 00:15:23,219
they can't really say, sometimes they don't believe they've had it.

151
00:15:23,519 --> 00:15:29,288
It's that subtle, it's that sort of underlying realization.

152
00:15:29,727 --> 00:15:33,254
But it's not big enough to be held, to be contemplated about.

153
00:15:34,095 --> 00:15:40,504
So the next one, when we rise to the next one, this once returner, he said it's like a starry night.

154
00:15:41,164 --> 00:15:46,552
So there you can hold, there's enough insight for it to be held and for it to be understood.

155
00:15:47,225 --> 00:15:53,855
But the anagami, the one who is not going to return, and we'll explain that in a minute, it's like a full moon.

156
00:15:54,034 --> 00:15:57,379
So it's very clear, but there's still this darkness around it.

157
00:15:57,780 --> 00:16:03,950
And finally, the arahat, the one who's fully liberated, is like the full moon, the full noonday sun.

158
00:16:04,451 --> 00:16:04,750
Okay.

159
00:16:07,434 --> 00:16:12,101
So one way of looking at this process is through these fetters.

160
00:16:12,452 --> 00:16:13,413
Sanyojana.

161
00:16:14,075 --> 00:16:19,041
So the word Sanyojana has the word yoga in it.

162
00:16:19,701 --> 00:16:31,455
And that fundamental, I think it's, I've looked it up, y-e-u-g is one of those words that comes right through the Indo-European languages.

163
00:16:31,634 --> 00:16:34,138
And our word yoke comes from the same place.

164
00:16:37,260 --> 00:16:38,663
So there are 10 of these words.

165
00:16:40,128 --> 00:16:46,379
And the first three are what goes when somebody has this little insight, this first insight.

166
00:16:46,399 --> 00:16:51,610
So the first one is this Sakyadity, which is translated as self-identity view.

167
00:16:52,230 --> 00:16:57,681
So it's basically the view, the notion, the belief that

168
00:16:58,183 --> 00:17:00,268
I am this human being.

169
00:17:00,508 --> 00:17:02,673
I am this person.

170
00:17:03,533 --> 00:17:11,308
So even at an intellectual level, when you talk about the body, well, we know it changes every seven years.

171
00:17:11,368 --> 00:17:13,874
They tell you all the cells have been changed by every seven years.

172
00:17:14,535 --> 00:17:19,825
So, I mean, I've almost had seven bodies, 11 bodies, I haven't seen.

173
00:17:19,845 --> 00:17:21,188
Time I got rid of it.

174
00:17:21,386 --> 00:17:31,384
And when you think about your thoughts and what you used to think when you were three years old and what you do now, your feelings, your emotions, you can see it's a flow of events, isn't it?

175
00:17:31,403 --> 00:17:33,929
It's just a flow of events moving one into the other.

176
00:17:34,449 --> 00:17:34,670
Yes?

177
00:17:35,832 --> 00:17:37,755
Is it okay to ask a question?

178
00:17:37,835 --> 00:17:38,316
At the end.

179
00:17:39,426 --> 00:17:40,048
Just hold it.

180
00:17:40,268 --> 00:17:40,568
Hold it.

181
00:17:40,989 --> 00:17:42,351
If you stop my flow, that's the end of it.

182
00:17:43,192 --> 00:17:45,996
So... Just one word.

183
00:17:46,016 --> 00:17:46,336
What word?

184
00:17:46,536 --> 00:17:47,417
Personality.

185
00:17:47,917 --> 00:17:49,460
Ah, well, personality.

186
00:17:49,780 --> 00:17:52,585
These words have lots of meanings in English.

187
00:17:52,944 --> 00:17:55,808
But what we're referring to is that sense of, this is me.

188
00:17:56,430 --> 00:18:00,214
So, however you want to describe that personality, your person, your character.

189
00:18:01,016 --> 00:18:05,801
But it's what you would write down if you said, I am.

190
00:18:06,041 --> 00:18:07,964
Whatever you finish that I am with,

191
00:18:08,636 --> 00:18:09,758
That's what you believe.

192
00:18:09,898 --> 00:18:11,339
That's what we believe ourselves to be.

193
00:18:11,861 --> 00:18:12,101
Okay.

194
00:18:13,923 --> 00:18:15,125
So it's undermining that.

195
00:18:16,066 --> 00:18:17,208
And now an identity.

196
00:18:17,248 --> 00:18:18,249
What is identity?

197
00:18:18,689 --> 00:18:21,512
Well, the example I use is when you bite your tongue.

198
00:18:21,893 --> 00:18:22,034
Right.

199
00:18:23,194 --> 00:18:26,439
So you're eating away and you're enjoying your food and you bite your tongue.

200
00:18:26,459 --> 00:18:31,505
So that for that one wonderful singular moment, you and the pain are completely one.

201
00:18:32,145 --> 00:18:32,906
Right.

202
00:18:33,612 --> 00:18:35,354
That's identity.

203
00:18:35,574 --> 00:18:39,458
Then you jump out of it and you find yourself a little angry with yourself.

204
00:18:39,818 --> 00:18:41,601
Now you've become anger, you see.

205
00:18:42,361 --> 00:18:48,288
So identity is when you lose that sense of objectivity about what you're experiencing is what you are at that moment.

206
00:18:48,969 --> 00:18:50,509
So you trap your finger in a door.

207
00:18:51,290 --> 00:18:53,073
Pain's wonderful at doing that for us.

208
00:18:53,913 --> 00:18:56,717
But sometimes great pleasure, great joy.

209
00:18:57,153 --> 00:18:59,377
Also, you absorb into it and become it.

210
00:18:59,417 --> 00:19:05,490
You lose that sense of somebody enjoying something, somebody feeling something.

211
00:19:05,751 --> 00:19:06,753
You are that feeling.

212
00:19:06,794 --> 00:19:10,761
You are that pleasure or that mental state.

213
00:19:11,564 --> 00:19:14,250
That's what we mean by identity.

214
00:19:17,268 --> 00:19:19,791
So that's the first fetter that goes.

215
00:19:20,192 --> 00:19:22,836
Now, we'll come back to that.

216
00:19:22,855 --> 00:19:24,498
The second one is doubt.

217
00:19:24,999 --> 00:19:27,122
So this is a particular type of doubt.

218
00:19:27,301 --> 00:19:29,164
It's the doubt that stops you doing anything.

219
00:19:29,826 --> 00:19:33,069
It's the doubt that will stop you from committing.

220
00:19:34,531 --> 00:19:43,404
So often you might find in life that you come across a certain situation like a job and you apply for it, but then you go through this doubt business.

221
00:19:43,525 --> 00:19:44,205
Can I do it?

222
00:19:44,226 --> 00:19:44,886
Should I do it?

223
00:19:44,906 --> 00:19:45,907
And all this sort of stuff.

224
00:19:46,494 --> 00:19:50,598
And sometimes that doubt, that self-doubt is so strong, you don't take the job.

225
00:19:50,799 --> 00:19:51,621
You lose it, you see.

226
00:19:52,040 --> 00:19:53,362
So you don't give yourself a chance.

227
00:19:53,962 --> 00:19:55,244
So it's the same in meditation.

228
00:19:55,444 --> 00:19:57,807
You sit and then you think, well, everybody else is amazing.

229
00:19:57,967 --> 00:19:58,929
I'm absolutely useless.

230
00:19:59,288 --> 00:20:02,853
And then you just say, and you keep convincing yourself that you're no good at it.

231
00:20:02,873 --> 00:20:03,773
So you may as well stop.

232
00:20:04,535 --> 00:20:05,915
So it's the same with the Buddha Dharma.

233
00:20:06,797 --> 00:20:13,144
You know, there may come a time when you think, well, I don't know whether the Buddha is right, whether it's Dharma for me, etc., etc.,

234
00:20:13,596 --> 00:20:17,143
But that goes completely with somebody who has this level of insight.

235
00:20:17,923 --> 00:20:24,875
There's no more of that sort of prevarication, that doubt, that oscillating doubt.

236
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:29,103
That's not the same as honest doubt.

237
00:20:29,222 --> 00:20:37,376
I mean, the Buddha actually wants us to investigate what he says because the process of investigation itself is the process of liberation.

238
00:20:38,740 --> 00:20:42,486
And then the third one is an attachment to rites and rituals.

239
00:20:43,067 --> 00:20:52,642
So this goes back to those times when, for instance, say in Hinduism, just to bathe in the Ganges would get rid of your karma.

240
00:20:53,123 --> 00:20:53,303
Right.

241
00:20:54,105 --> 00:20:57,150
That reminds you of something I met.

242
00:20:57,490 --> 00:21:00,494
This is years ago when I went out there as a sort of pseudo hippie.

243
00:21:00,661 --> 00:21:02,523
And I met this young woman.

244
00:21:02,544 --> 00:21:04,686
I was young myself, of course, in those wonderful days.

245
00:21:05,387 --> 00:21:12,498
And I went to this yoga center and she was there and she had all these spots and things all over her face.

246
00:21:12,878 --> 00:21:13,660
I said, what happened?

247
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:22,772
She said, well, you know, I went down to the Ganges and joined them in this washing, in this, you know, getting rid of karma.

248
00:21:23,134 --> 00:21:24,134
And I drank some of it.

249
00:21:24,957 --> 00:21:25,857
And I said, what?

250
00:21:27,813 --> 00:21:34,183
And not only does everybody's toilet goes into the Ganges, we get dead bodies of all sorts, even humans.

251
00:21:34,944 --> 00:21:41,215
And this poor woman was just getting over what looked like almost blood poisoning or something.

252
00:21:41,236 --> 00:21:42,597
And she's getting over it.

253
00:21:44,991 --> 00:21:53,201
So, like, I mean, we do little rituals like lighting candles, repeating the refuges and precepts.

254
00:21:53,602 --> 00:22:06,256
But if we were to believe that that was a part, that itself would help us to become liberated, then that, of course, would be a severe delusion, right?

255
00:22:06,277 --> 00:22:14,526
So it's going back to those days where people might have thought certain rituals, undergoing certain rituals were cleansing.

256
00:22:16,784 --> 00:22:27,615
So that would then be undermined by this insight, which would be telling the person who has it that the path is one of purification.

257
00:22:27,976 --> 00:22:40,869
So remember, the Buddha only taught two things, the path of purification, which is getting rid of all these defilements within us, and the path of insight, which is seeing things as they really are.

258
00:22:40,890 --> 00:22:43,333
So what do we mean when we say things really are?

259
00:22:43,373 --> 00:22:45,474
Well, we mean how we cause suffering,

260
00:22:46,113 --> 00:22:52,161
So there's the process of desire and how it leads us into a certain ways of attachment.

261
00:22:53,142 --> 00:23:01,333
How that attachment then begins to create people, situations, things that we don't like.

262
00:23:01,452 --> 00:23:06,960
Because as soon as you're attached to something, you're cutting off the other bit that you're not attached to.

263
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:09,403
So you immediately create a conflict.

264
00:23:09,990 --> 00:23:11,732
And then there's impermanence, right?

265
00:23:11,752 --> 00:23:14,376
So that's the three things, dukkha and ichanata.

266
00:23:14,396 --> 00:23:20,585
And impermanence is really, really driving home that everything comes to an end.

267
00:23:21,306 --> 00:23:30,818
I mean, we're very good at noticing beginnings, you know, the beginning of a film, the beginning of a... Well, you see these pop stars come and then they sort of disappear.

268
00:23:30,838 --> 00:23:31,779
You don't know what happened to them.

269
00:23:32,451 --> 00:23:34,074
There's all things like that.

270
00:23:34,094 --> 00:23:37,057
It's really beginning to recognize that everything comes to an end.

271
00:23:37,176 --> 00:23:43,103
So after you finish a meal to recognize this is, you know, like one less lunch in this lifetime.

272
00:23:43,722 --> 00:23:47,626
After you finish the day, this is one day less of my living.

273
00:23:48,147 --> 00:23:55,675
And it's sort of slowly driving it home, coming to terms with the fact of what impermanence really means for us.

274
00:23:55,915 --> 00:23:56,115
Yeah.

275
00:23:56,717 --> 00:24:01,040
So our gaze is always averted towards the beginning and sustaining.

276
00:24:01,492 --> 00:24:04,616
So as soon as the ending comes, we're thinking of something else.

277
00:24:05,458 --> 00:24:06,980
We're on to the next film.

278
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:08,241
We're on to the next holiday.

279
00:24:08,722 --> 00:24:10,084
What am I going to do when I retire?

280
00:24:11,145 --> 00:24:13,990
What am I going to do when I retire?

281
00:24:15,191 --> 00:24:18,736
And the final one is this, of course, the anatta, this not-self.

282
00:24:18,756 --> 00:24:27,788
So the easiest way to investigate this anatta is, he states it in the discourse on not-self.

283
00:24:28,087 --> 00:24:36,519
is to see what, when you talk about this body or this mind or my mental state, how much control have we got of it?

284
00:24:36,739 --> 00:24:38,401
How much control do we have over it?

285
00:24:39,061 --> 00:24:41,826
Then you realize that your control isn't absolute.

286
00:24:42,026 --> 00:24:45,990
So if your control is not absolute over something, it can't be you.

287
00:24:47,032 --> 00:24:51,057
That's the definition of me, that I'm in control.

288
00:24:51,358 --> 00:24:53,321
So that's how he begins the discourse.

289
00:24:53,342 --> 00:24:59,330
He said, if this body were mine, I'd make it grow taller, I'd make my hair grow more, etc., etc.

290
00:24:59,991 --> 00:25:00,553
But you can't.

291
00:25:00,692 --> 00:25:02,536
There are certain things you simply can't do.

292
00:25:02,615 --> 00:25:11,490
So we find that this sense of control over us, over this organism, is quite surface.

293
00:25:12,070 --> 00:25:20,303
I can move my arms around and all that, but I can do things with my body, but once my back goes, that's the end of it.

294
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:22,701
Yeah, I've learned that the hard way.

295
00:25:25,124 --> 00:25:32,951
So all those three chains, shackles, disappear.

296
00:25:34,333 --> 00:25:43,862
That fundamental idea of identity, even though the notion is snapped, it still stays with us to the very end as conceit.

297
00:25:45,182 --> 00:25:49,948
So it's not as though you get rid of that sense of self just because you've had this insight.

298
00:25:49,988 --> 00:25:51,048
The doubt goes...

299
00:25:51,298 --> 00:25:57,846
though it may reappear in different forms, but doubt in the Dharma itself is usually rock solid.

300
00:25:58,788 --> 00:26:05,376
Sorry, faith in the Dharma itself is usually rock solid.

301
00:26:05,396 --> 00:26:14,127
And a distinction between why you do little rituals and they're not actually going to create salvation or purification.

302
00:26:14,147 --> 00:26:18,453
So that word salvation, although it's a Christian word, it actually does mean healing.

303
00:26:20,492 --> 00:26:31,243
Now, it's only until we come to the second level, the once returner, that these two major things are undermined, which is our sensual desires and all our aversions.

304
00:26:32,484 --> 00:26:33,945
But they're only attenuated.

305
00:26:34,026 --> 00:26:36,588
They're not actually destroyed.

306
00:26:37,028 --> 00:26:40,573
And that only happens when you get to the third level, the non-returner.

307
00:26:40,853 --> 00:26:46,578
So that's why a person who's at the third level doesn't come back because they're not interested in sensual pleasure anymore.

308
00:26:46,699 --> 00:26:47,799
It's as simple as that.

309
00:26:48,151 --> 00:26:55,106
And their happiness comes from these absorptions and these beautiful mental states that they can achieve.

310
00:26:56,233 --> 00:27:08,290
So finally, when we get to Arahant, these two things, the jhana, these absorptions, are now no longer places to indulge.

311
00:27:08,652 --> 00:27:12,798
It doesn't mean to say that they can't achieve them, because the Buddha was often going through the jhanas.

312
00:27:13,318 --> 00:27:19,788
But they weren't something that they would be attached to as a source of personal pleasure.

313
00:27:21,651 --> 00:27:23,153
So the awareness would always be there.

314
00:27:23,757 --> 00:27:27,221
Finally, this conceit goes, which is that sense of I am.

315
00:27:27,621 --> 00:27:30,743
So conceit always draws us into a comparison.

316
00:27:30,763 --> 00:27:32,165
So I'm better than somebody.

317
00:27:32,185 --> 00:27:33,227
All right.

318
00:27:33,247 --> 00:27:34,367
So that's obvious pride.

319
00:27:34,868 --> 00:27:38,492
I'm worse than somebody that often masquerades as humility.

320
00:27:38,613 --> 00:27:41,095
You know, I'm not as good as so-and-so, you know.

321
00:27:41,115 --> 00:27:44,057
And then finally, there's a more subtle one about we.

322
00:27:46,221 --> 00:27:49,443
So.

323
00:27:49,541 --> 00:28:03,818
If I say, well, I'm right, and I can get a few other people to say, I'm right, I agree with you, this sense of I, of the conceit, grows because now it becomes we.

324
00:28:04,380 --> 00:28:07,123
It's not just I believe this, it's we believe this.

325
00:28:07,884 --> 00:28:19,076
So there's that more subtle sense of conceit, whereas normally we might think, oh, well, that's not conceit, that's not pride, but it's just an extension of our conceit.

326
00:28:20,827 --> 00:28:21,970
Restlessness goes.

327
00:28:22,329 --> 00:28:28,900
This restlessness is all the remaining defilements that are there.

328
00:28:29,480 --> 00:28:36,330
But now they're so fine, they're so disempowered that they finally just disappear.

329
00:28:37,011 --> 00:28:40,676
But it's understood that even after...

330
00:28:41,045 --> 00:28:45,791
even after liberation, there are still traces of those habits in the mind.

331
00:28:46,292 --> 00:28:50,439
And if you read what Meichi Kyao says, that's exactly what she says.

332
00:28:50,499 --> 00:29:00,173
She says she still gets these little traces in the mind of greed, aversion and delusive ideas, but none of them ever enter into her heart.

333
00:29:00,894 --> 00:29:04,740
So in other words, this sense of awareness is always something distinct.

334
00:29:05,161 --> 00:29:06,563
And that's where she is.

335
00:29:07,723 --> 00:29:17,016
And then finally, that ignorance, really, that's just a blanket statement that all ignorance has gone and the delusion that arises from it.

336
00:29:17,416 --> 00:29:22,623
And that fundamental ignorance, of course, is the definition of who I am.

337
00:29:23,724 --> 00:29:31,575
So these are your 10 fetters and they are shackles.

338
00:29:31,994 --> 00:29:35,519
So if they're shackles, something must be unshackling.

339
00:29:35,737 --> 00:29:38,920
So something is being shackled by these shackles.

340
00:29:40,401 --> 00:29:44,884
So what we discover, of course, is that the very thing that's being unshackled is awareness.

341
00:29:45,705 --> 00:29:51,151
So every time you sit in meditation and you see an object, that object can't be you.

342
00:29:52,030 --> 00:30:05,202
No matter what you're seeing inside yourself, whether it's a feeling or a thought or some sort of physical sensation, as soon as you turn it into an object, this awareness is separating out from it.

343
00:30:05,571 --> 00:30:09,779
And that process of separation is the process of unshackling.

344
00:30:10,501 --> 00:30:14,990
And that's where the sense of release comes from, the sense of relief.

345
00:30:15,371 --> 00:30:19,358
And that's why the Buddha says the taste of Nibbana is freedom.

346
00:30:20,161 --> 00:30:22,685
Yeah, the taste of Nibbana is freedom.

347
00:30:31,221 --> 00:30:31,643
That's it.

348
00:30:32,424 --> 00:30:35,330
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

349
00:30:36,153 --> 00:30:41,044
That it has not driven you into deep sleep and somnolence.

350
00:30:41,064 --> 00:30:47,037
And that by your diligence you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

